bal Culture, and Globalization: A Diachronic Perspective -- tGlossary -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of sustainability holds that the social, economic, and environmental factors within human communities must be viewed interactively and systematically. Sustainable development cannot be understood apart from a community, its ethos, and ways of life. Although broadly conceived, the pursuit of sustainable development is a local practice because every community has different needs and quality of life concerns. Within this framework, contributors representing the disciplines of anthropology, sociology, geography, economics, law, public policy, architecture, and urban studies explore sustainability in communities in the Pacific, Latin America, Sub-Saharan Africa, Eastern Europe, and North America. Contributors: Janet E. Benson, Karla Caser, Snjezana Colic, Angela Ferreira, Johanna Gibson, Krista Harper, Paulo Lana, Barbara Yablon Maida, Carl A. Maida, Kenneth A. Meter, Dario Novellino, Deborah Pellow, Claude Raynaut, Thomas F. Thornton, Richard Westra, Magda Zanoni  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCommunity life. 0aSustainable development. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh1 aBenson, Janet E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaser, Karla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColic, Snjezana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Krista, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca